Synonyms he defines in the sentence immediately following this definition Of the homonym: Συνώνυμα δὲ λέγεται ὧν τό τε ὄνομα κοινὸν καὶ ὁ κατὰ τοῦνομα λόγος τῆς οὐσίας ὃ αὐτός, οἷον ζῴον ὅ τε ἅνθρωπος καὶ ὃ βοῦς. - “ Synonyms are defined as ob- J'ects which have their name in common, and of which the defi- nition of the real substance is the same: as ζῴον denotes man and ox.”

In these rather formal definitions‚ Aristotle is regarding homonyms and synonyms as objects and not as mere words. 'Synonyms consequently appear to him as different objects comprised under one class-name. Homonyms, on the other hand, are objects having the same name but not belonging to the same class. Man and ox are synonyms, because they come under the same class-name of animal.
